🔥 Hot Take: Remote work isn't broken—your culture is.

"I don't really care what Silicon Valley companies do. I care about what my teammates want to be doing. A lot of my teammates have families, kids—they need to drop their kids off at 3 PM. It's fine by me."

Anjali Menon, Co-founder of tbh, just called out the return-to-office obsession with this refreshingly human approach to remote work.

While other founders panic about "culture" and force people back into offices, Anjali's team at tbh (mental health support for schools and businesses) is thriving virtually:
✅ Self-selecting for people who thrive remotely
✅ Building culture INTO their virtual environment
✅ Having a "company culture king" who creates custom Slack bots and games
✅ Friday selfie contests and team voting—all in Slack

Her secret? Stop fighting remote work and start intentionally designing for it. They're "24-7 on Slack" because that's where they've chosen to live their work lives.

🎯 Founder Takeaway: Remote culture isn't an accident—it's architecture. Build the virtual environment your team actually wants to work in, not what Silicon Valley says you should want. 

#WhyWorkHere #RemoteWork #CompanyCulture #HotTake

Hiring reality tip: Why polished job postings attract the wrong people

Here's what doesn't work: Sanitized corporate speak that hides the real job requirements and culture. 

Here's what does work: Brutal honesty that makes people self-select in or out.

Executive search expert, Zaharo Tsekouras, tested this with two extreme companies:

Consciousness-focused venture firm → Went full "woo woo" in the job description → Got candidates who actually cared about inner work and expansion

Hardcore hedge fund → Posted "no vacation for 2 years, 16-hour days" upfront → Went viral, attracted candidates who were genuinely excited about the grind

🎯 The brutal truth: Authentic posts work because they repel people who don't belong and magnetize those who do.

For job seekers: Stop applying to companies that won't tell you what they're really about. If they're hiding their culture in the job posting, imagine what they're hiding once you're hired.

The best candidates want transparency, not fairy tales.

This comes from our recruiting panel "Bridging the Gap Between Hiring Team Expectations & Market Reality" where industry experts share what's really happening in today's hiring landscape.

What's the most brutally honest job posting you've seen? Did it make you more or less interested? 👇

#HiringReality #JobPostings #RecruiterTruth #Wellfound #Transparency

🎯 Founder Tip: "We show our books. Everything my finance team knows, my whole company knows."

JJ Tang's radical transparency at Rootly:
✅ Bi-weekly all-hands with full financials
✅ Cash flow, burn rate, revenue—everything exposed
✅ Self-aware culture over celebration culture

Result? Employees think like owners because they have owner-level information.

💡 Key Insight: Transparency creates ownership. Ownership drives performance. 

#WhyWorkHere #StartupTransparency #Rootly #OpenBooks

💡 Founder Tip: The best startup ideas come from being in the room when things go wrong.

Zachary Conway was pitching investment management the old way. Throwing slides at clients, talking about credentials, pushing generic products.

The feedback? "That experience was horrible. You didn't ask me about my values or what I actually care about.

"That brutal honesty in the room sparked Seeds. Now they're rebuilding the financial advisory from the ground up.

🚀 Takeaway: Join companies where the founder has felt the customer's pain firsthand. 

#WhyWorkHere #FinTech #Seeds #StartupCulture

You're doing job applications wrong (and so is everyone else)

❌ Hit "apply" and pray for a response
✅ Apply, then immediately connect

Jassi Starleaf, Senior Talent Partner at Learneo, breaks down why 99% of candidates disappear into the void: They apply and vanish.

Here's what works:

Apply with personalized examples → Look for people you know at the company or find recruiters/team members on LinkedIn → Send a short message about what excites you about the role

As Jassi puts it: "Be genuine and show your enthusiasm. Keep it light and sweet.

"While everyone else sends resumes into the black hole, you're having an actual conversation. What's your move after hitting "apply"? 👇 

#JobSearch #CareerAdvice #Recruiting #JobHunting

💡 Startup Tip: Polite disruption beats aggressive disruption in legacy industries.

Most tech companies enter legacy industries saying "You've done it wrong, here's our amazing solution."

Zachary Conway at Seeds takes a different approach with financial advisors who've run their businesses for decades.

"Threading that needle is so critical. How we frame messaging, onboard customers, drive success. That's politely disruptive vs. 'you're terrible and need our technology.'"

🚀 Takeaway: Join companies that respect their customers' expertise while solving real problems. 

#WhyWorkHere #StartupStrategy #Seeds #LegacyIndustries

💡 Job Search Tip: This AI trick will change how you negotiate salary

Most people walk into salary talks completely unprepared. Here's what Jassi Starleaf, Senior Talent Partner at Learneo, does instead:

🌟 Practice with ChatGPT first.

Seriously. Ask it: "What if they counter with this number?" or "How do I respond when they say the budget is tight?"

Why this works: You get comfortable with the awkward back-and-forth before real money is on the table.

Plot twist: Even in today's brutal job market, we actually have more negotiation power than ever. Salary transparency laws force companies to show their cards. Research tools give you real data. AI gives you free coaching.

Want to know what you should be asking for? Check out our salary calculator: https://wellfound.com/hiring-data 

Have you tried practicing negotiations with AI? 

#SalaryNegotiation #AITools #CareerTips

🔎 Job Search Tip: What startup founders really want in interviews

Alyssa Previti, HR Director at Wellfound, decodes those awkward "startup culture" questions. She recommends candidates:
✅ Show drive and initiative
✅ Share A-to-Z project examples
✅ Prove you can work independently
❌ Don't assume it's about committing to long hours

Why it matters: Most founders are new to hiring and ask clunky questions, but they're really looking for someone who thrives when "we don't have things figured out yet."

What's your startup interview experience?

#JobSearch #StartupJobs #InterviewTips #CareerAdvice

🎯 Founder Tip: "We tell candidates how hard it is to work here, how bad it is to work here. And they're still excited."

JJ Tang's radical hiring honesty at Rootly:
✅ Full transparency about challenges
✅ Self-selecting top talent
✅ High talent density

Result? Wrong-fit hires leave in week one. Right-fit hires thrive.

💡 Key Insight: The best companies attract people who see challenges as opportunities.

#WhyWorkHere #StartupHiring #Rootly #HiringTransparency

Job Search Tip 🔥 Hot Take: "You are expensive" - what startups really think about Big Tech workers

Hilary Gardner from Inspiren gets brutally honest: Google/Meta/Amazon workers are seen as overpriced and unproven.
Her strategy:
✅ Negotiate equity & sign-ons instead
✅ Focus on the RIGHT environment over the RIGHT pay

#JobSearch #BigTech #StartupJobs #Wellfound
